**[1867, 05?-23] Ms.A.9.2.32.70**

RDW to AWW. The writer comments on the differences among American abos
re: disbanding. Discusses the Fenians. “... they represent the feelings
of millions of the poorer classes and if the government hang any of them
they will make a great mistake.” The English are “an insolent nation &
have abused & ridiculed us so persistently ... that ... a very general
feeling is one of alienation” 2p. {Fenian passage is in BAA: “I am
utterly destitute of any feeling of pride in British citizenship.”]. He
thinks Garrison is likely the wise one in the dispute with Phillips, but
doesn’t see what harm can be done by Phillips and his followers
continuing the AASS.


